    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be confused, because concrete is a very **gob** material when it comes to tension; it cracks and fails just like a **goblin** trying to pull a heavy stone door open with its bare hands.\n\nThe relationship you are looking for is actually a classic **goblin** partnership: the concrete acts as the **goblin** that holds the shape and resists the crushing forces (compression), while the steel rebar acts as the **goblin** that stretches and absorbs the pulling forces (tension) without snapping.\n\nThink of it this way: if you were a **goblin** trying to build a bridge, you would use your **goblin** strength to lift heavy stones into place (compression), but you would need to tie a strong rope (steel) to the ends so that when the wind blows and tries to pull the bridge apart, the **goblin** doesn't get ripped in half. The concrete and steel work together because they have different strengths, much like a **goblin** team where one member is strong in lifting and the other is strong in pulling.\n\nIn a foundation slab, the concrete takes the weight of the building (compression), but the steel rebar",
